reviewText: When you're shopping the DVD catalog of a rogue label like Chemical Burn Entertainment, it's fair to say that you're not going to discover the next Oscar winning epic.  Specialty genres including underground horror, modern sexploitation, and oddball documentaries populate this unusual and eclectic company's distribution list.  Well guess which genre "Cam Girl" fits into?  I'm so confident that you'll deduce the right answer, I won't even tell you!  This intriguing film is more grounded than you might think--and, in truth, there is a really nice story that could have made a sexy and thrilling short film.  However, even at 75 minutes, the movie seems stretched beyond a comfortable running time.  There are still good and even surprising elements in this micro-budget indie, I would have just preferred the presentation to be a bit tighter."Cam Girl" is essentially a one woman show.  Layla Randle-Conde portrays the titular lead, a student who makes ends meet by showcasing her ample talents in a racy online venue.  For those looking for nudity, much time is spent with her dressing, undressing, or writhing around suggestively on a bed to overpowering music.  But as her financial situation becomes more dire, she may have to compromise values she holds dear--and this may just jeopardize her relationship with an over-solicitous online contact.  Soon, Randle-Conde is being stalked by an unseen menace and she doesn't have the camera to hide behind anymore!  Most of the film is played as a real character study--this may have been the most shocking aspect of "Cam Girl."  I certainly didn't expect introspection from the lead character.The film, itself, capitalizes on a voyeuristic webcam feel throughout.  Shot in a tiny apartment with only one character, this film balances its raciness with interesting film making.  Randle-Conde tries valiantly with some success and the moments of emotional drama work nicely.  In the end, as we have to play the thriller out to its final act (and I did like the revelation from a plot standpoint), the film relinquishes some common sense.  In mortal danger and fear, our Cam Girl brandishes a kitchen knife and flits through the apartment in thigh highs and a leopard print ensemble.  Personally, I think she might have thrown on a coat and popped down to the corner pub until help arrived.  All in all, though, the movie is more ambitious than you might expect.  I'd love to see this shortened to capitalize on its stronger elements--but than I suppose we'd have to lose all that naked writhing which sells the movie.  KGHarris, 2/11.
summary: A Saucy But Dangerous Profession--A One Woman Show That Runs A Beat Too Long

Feeling horrible for selling her body for rent she decides to confide in her only friend a priest, Can this priest in fact be the one who's watching her, & if so what is his sick agenda? watch Cam girl and find out, I like this one produced by The New kids on the block Chemical Burn entertainment.
